y inhabit, whether by direct action, rallies, marches, organized work stoppages, or engaging government power in service of their aims. Active Voices explores both the rhetorical dimensions of such activist activities and the integral role of rhetoric in the processes of social transformation. This collection balances in-depth analyses of particular movements and pedagogical projects with broader perspectives on how language and embodied action shape avenues for activism. Featured are a wide range of sites for social change, from the progressive education movement to African American drum circles, and from prisoner reentry programs to the nineteenth-century women's suffrage movement. Speaking as scholars, activists, storytellers, rhetoricians, and teachers, the contributors blur the boundaries between different aspects of their identities and challenge divisions between creating theory and practicing it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspects. 0aRhetoricxSocial aspects. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aCommunication : Political Communication. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh1 aAmado-Miller, Moira K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCain, Mary Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoogan, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegenaro, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHauser, Gerard A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalesh, Patricia M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMalesh, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l